PSEUDOCODE
==========

Enable clock for GPIOA
Configure PA5 as output (push-pull, no pull-up/down, low speed)
Loop forever:
    Set PA5 HIGH
    Wait ~500ms
    Set PA5 LOW
    Wait ~500ms

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA5  =>  Onboard LED (LD4) - Active HIGH

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

RCC (Reset and Clock Control)
|-------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register    | Field          | Description                                                                                  |
|-------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| RCC->IOPENR | IOPAEN (bit 0) | Enables the clock for GPIOA. Without this, any write to GPIOA registers is silently ignored. |
|-------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

GPIOA (General-Purpose Input/Output Port A)
|----------------|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register       | Field                       | Description                                                                                   |
|----------------|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| GPIOA->MODER   | bits[11:10] for PA5         | Sets pin mode. 01 = General purpose output. Reset value is 11 (analog) for most pins.         |
| GPIOA->OTYPER  | bit 5                       | Output type. 0 = Push-pull, 1 = Open-drain. We use push-pull.                                 |
| GPIOA->OSPEEDR | bits[11:10] for PA5         | Output speed. 00 = Low speed. Fine for LED.                                                   |
| GPIOA->PUPDR   | bits[11:10] for PA5         | Pull-up/Pull-down. 00 = None. Output pins don't need it.                                      |
| GPIOA->BSSR    | bit 5 (SET), bit 21 (RESET) | Atomic set/reset of pin. Write 1 to bit 5 to set PA5 HIGH. Write 1 to bit 21 to pull PA5 LOW. |
| GPIOA->ODR     | bit 5                       | Direct output data register. Can also be used to drive the pin, but not atomic.               |
|----------------|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Forgetting RCC->IOPENR - The most common first mistake. GPIO registers exist
  in memory but writes do nothing until the peripheral clock is enabled. If our
  LED never turns on, this is the first thing to check.

* Not clearing MODER bits before setting, MODER reset value for PA5 is 10
  (analog mode on most pins). If we only |= without first clearing with 
  &= ~(3U << 10), we may land in an unintended mode.

* Using ODR instead of BSRR, ODR is not atomic. In a simple blink it doesn't
  matter, but in ISR-driven code doing ODR ^= (1 << 5) is a read-modify-write
  and can be corrupted. Build the BSRR habit now.

* Software delay is not accurate - The delay() here is purely a loop
  counter. Compiler optimizations can shrink or eliminate it. Use volatile on
  the counter (done above) and don't expect real milliseconds from this. That's
  what SysTick is for.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* Why IOPORT_BASE is separate from PERIPH_BASE, On STM32G0, GPIO peripherals sit
  on the IOPORT bus (0x50000000) rather than the standard APB/AHB bus
  (0x40000000). This is a G0-specific thing. On STM32F4 for example, all GPIOs
  are on AHB1. Keep this in mind when reading reference manuals for other
  families.

* BSRR (Bit Set Reset Register) breakdown, the upper 16 bits (BR, bits [31:16])
  reset a pin and the lower 16 bits (BS, bits [15:0]) set a pin. Writing both in
  the same write is atomic. If we write BSRR = (1 << 5) | (1 << 21), the reset
  side wins. Useful to know.

* volatile on register structs, Every field in the struct is marked
  volatile. This tells the compiler: do not cache this, do not reorder this,
  always read/write from actual memory. Without it, the compiler may optimize
  the register writes away entirely.

* This program is the skeleton for everything that follows: The RCC enable +
  MODER config pattern repeats for every peripheral tied to a GPIO pin.

